R Notebook: Descriptive Stats and Visuals

This is an R Markdown Notebook. When you execute code within the notebook, the results appear beneath the code.

Dante’s View in Death Valley National Park

Data for this example comes from the USGS

getwd()
## [1] "C:/Users/User/Documents/R/USGSquakes"

Lets load the data in from a CSV file

quakes <- read.csv("all_month.csv")

now lets take a look at the table to start

head(quakes)

now we will go in and do summary statistics on “mag”

summary(quakes$mag)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.    NA's 
##  -0.820   0.730   1.300   1.585   2.000   7.900       1
sd(quakes$mag, na.rm=TRUE)
## [1] 1.23015

Now lets look at a simple histogram of the magnitude

hist(quakes$mag)
rug(quantile(quakes$mag, na.rm = TRUE), col=2, lwd=2.5)

lets get the quartile values

quantile(quakes$mag, probs = c(0, 0.25, 0.5, 0.75, 1), na.rm = TRUE)
##    0%   25%   50%   75%  100% 
## -0.82  0.73  1.30  2.00  7.90

Now lets look at the normal qq plot of this same data, another way to look at distribution

qqnorm(quakes$mag)

Now lets look at the depth with the same plots

hist(quakes$depth)

qqnorm(quakes$depth)

now lets look at a scatter plot magnitude vs. depth

plot(quakes$depth, quakes$mag, main="Scatterplot",
     xlab="Depth", ylab="Magnitude")

Lets to box plots of depts by magnitude but first we cut the continuous value of magnitude into bins

quakes$maggroup <- round(quakes$mag,digits=0)
head(quakes)

Now we’ll do boxplots

boxplot(depth~maggroup, data=quakes, main="USGS earthquake data",
        xlab="Magnitude", ylab="Depth")

So we see a lot of outliers showing up in the magnitude 4 and 5 ranges

Lets now calculate the standard deviation values for each of the magnitude values

quakes$MagStdDev = ((quakes$mag - 1.585)/1.23015)
head(quakes)

Now lets get percentiles from that:

quakes$magpcent = pnorm(quakes$MagStdDev)*100
head(quakes)

Lets try a box plot of magnitude by reporting network

boxplot(mag~net, data=quakes, main="USGS earthquake data",
        xlab="reporting network", ylab="Magnitude")
